result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both Operating w/ PAC (4th w/in 5 yrs) and OWI (4th w/in 5 yrs). The defendant was found guilty of Operating w/ PAC (4th w/in 5 yrs) and the other charge, OWI (4th w/in 5 yrs) was dismissed by the court.

  • Brian T Schultz was found guilty of Operating w/ PAC (4th w/in 5 yrs), a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Brian T Schultz in court with Attorney Michael a Verrilli.  Brian J. Juech appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant enters a no contest plea to Count #2.  Court performs plea colloquy and finds Defendant guilty of Count #2.  Count #1 is dismissed by operation of law.   State gives sentencing recommendations.  Chad B. makes statements.  Attorney Verrilli makes statements regarding sentencing.  Defendant makes statements.  Court sentences the Defendant to the following:

COUNT #2:  IMPOSED AND STAYED SENTENCE OF:   

42 MONTHS IMPRISONMENT (CREDIT - __ days)
  -  2 YEARS OF INITIAL CONFINEMENT
  -  18 MONTHS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION;

*D/L REVOCATION:  30 months.
*IGNITION INTERLOCK:  30 months.

TERM OF PROBATION:  2 YEARS;

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION:  
*AODA Assessment and follow through with any treatment recommended;
*Absolute Sobriety;  Random U.A.'s ; 
*No Use or Possession of alcohol or illegal drugs 
*No Use or Possession of prescription drugs without a valid prescription;
*Any valid prescription drugs must be taken only in the manner in which they are prescribed/sign releases.
*Follow through with any treatment and/or counseling recommended by Agent;
*Maintain employment and/or combination of schooling 
*DNA sample to be provided if not yet previously done 
*Not to operate a motor vehicle without a valid driver's license 
*90 days of Day Report Center consecutive to condition time (see below) 
*Attendance at Victim Impact Panel - Defendant completed but court orders Defendant to attend an additional session 
 
FINE:  $1,771.00 & $250.00 DNA surcharge (to be paid out of cash bail posted ($750.00) and remainder as a condition of probation);

CONDITION TIME:  HUBER:  300 DAYS, LAST 60 DAYS STAYED.  Release for work, treatment.  Defendant taken into custody.  Court authorizes huber time to be transferred to Walworth County.  

DAY REPORT CENTER:  90 DAYS, Consecutive to Huber sentence.  Good time not allowed on DRC.  If defendant successfully completes Day Report Center, the 60 days of Huber stayed will be permanently stayed. 
 
Defendant is not eligible for Challenge Incarceration Program.
Defendant is eligible for Substance Abuse Program.
